    "solution": "<p><p>When benzene is nitrated, it forms nitrobenzene (benzene with a $-\\mathrm{NO}_2$ group).</p></p>\n<p><p>Now, Friedel–Crafts acylation ($\\mathrm{CH}_3\\mathrm{COCl}/\\mathrm{AlCl}_3$) needs an aromatic ring that is sufficiently reactive to attack the electrophile.</p></p>\n<p><p>The $-\\mathrm{NO}_2$ group is a strongly deactivating group. It pulls electron density away from the benzene ring, so the ring becomes much less reactive.</p></p>\n<p><p>Because of this strong deactivation, nitrobenzene does <b>not</b> undergo Friedel–Crafts acylation with $\\mathrm{CH}_3\\mathrm{COCl}/\\mathrm{AlCl}_3$.</p></p>\n<p><p>So, nitrobenzene will not give the shown acylated product under these conditions.</p></p>",
    "__v": 0,
    "title": "JEE Main 2026 (Online) 22nd January Morning Shift",
    "exam": "JEE Main"
  },
